{
  "doc_id": "31085",
  "text": "ASST paradigms are highly analogous to the Wisconsin Card Sorting Task (WCST) which has been extensively studied in patients with schizophrenia [CITATION_1] ) and can be a useful clinical marker in schizophrenia [CITATION_2] . Brd1 +/À mice displayed impaired performance in the extradimensional shift tasks. These deficits indicate a state of cognitive inflexibility as reported in patients suffering from schizophrenia [CITATION_3] . The ability to form attentional sets was intact in Brd1 +/À mice, thus demonstrating that their cognitive deficits are not global, but selective, as in schizophrenia [CITATION_4] . Reversal learning deficits which have been reported in patients with schizophrenia [CITATION_5] were, however, not found in Brd1 +/À mice, suggesting that their cortical dysfunction is more pronounced in certain frontal regions than others. Specifically, in mice, the medial prefrontal cortex (PFC) is implicated in short-, and long term memory [CITATION_6] as well as fear memories [CITATION_7] . In the ASST paradigm, ED shifting performance is impaired in humans with damage to the dorsolateral prefrontal cortex (PFC) [CITATION_8] , but the functionally homologue region in rodents is the medial PFC [CITATION_9] [CITATION_10] [CITATION_11] . Reversal learning performance, on the other hand, depends on orbitofrontal functioning across species [CITATION_12] [CITATION_13] [CITATION_14] and is independent of mPFC function [CITATION_15] . Besides medial prefrontal abnormalities, cue-and context dependent associative memory deficits in Brd1",
